04224nam a22005055i 9780300142976DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001429767 a10.12987/97803001429762doi  a(DE-B1597)485480  a(OCoLC)1024006716  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aHIS0210002bisacsh1 aHurst I, G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArmed Martial Arts of Japan :bSwordsmanship and Archery /cG. Hurst I. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b21 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTo the memory of Professor Nakabayashi Shinji -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE. Martial Arts and Japanese Culture -- tCHAPTER TWO. The Early Tradition -- tCHAPTER THREE. From Self-Protection to Self-Perfection in the Early and Mid Tokugawa -- tCHAPTER FOUR. The Sporting Element in the Late Tokugawa -- tCHAPTER FIVE. The Way of the Bow and Arrow -- tCHAPTER SIX. The Quest for Records in the Tokugawa -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Swordsmanship and Archery: The Modern Transformation -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. The Martial and Other Japanese Arts -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis unique history of Japanese armed martial arts-the only comprehensive treatment of the subject in English-focuses on traditions of swordsmanship and archery from ancient times to the present. G. Cameron Hurst III provides an overview of martial arts in Japanese history and culture, then closely examines the transformation of these fighting skills into sports. He discusses the influence of the Western athletic tradition on the armed martial arts as well as the ways the martial arts have remained distinctly Japanese.During the Tokugawa era (1600-1867), swordsmanship and archery developed from fighting systems into martial arts, transformed by the powerful social forces of peace, urbanization, literacy, and professionalized instruction in art forms. Hurst investigates the changes that occurred as military skills that were no longer necessary took on new purposes: physical fitness, spiritual composure, character development, and sport. He also considers Western misperceptions of Japanese traditional martial arts and argues that, contrary to common views in the West, Zen Buddhism is associated with the martial arts in only a limited way. The author concludes by exploring the modern organization, teaching, ritual, and philosophy of archery and swordsmanship; relating these martial arts to other art forms and placing them in the broader context of Japanese culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300142976423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300142976.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles